ob": 0.9805463552474976, "span": {"begin": 1543, "end": 1578}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3284"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "3B-HSD", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955379366874695, "span": {"begin": 1580, "end": 1586}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9923254251480103, "span": {"begin": 1629, "end": 1636}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1586"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Steroid 17-alpha-hydroxylase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9400498867034912, "span": {"begin": 1629, "end": 1657}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1586"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP17A1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9929888844490051, "span": {"begin": 1659, "end": 1666}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:35343"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17-beta-hydroxysteroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990860819816589, "span": {"begin": 1710, "end": 1732}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3292"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "17B-HSD", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9945105314254761, "span": {"begin": 1748, "end": 1755}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8973128199577332, "span": {"begin": 1798, "end": 1807}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP19A1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9950872659683228, "span": {"begin": 1809, "end": 1816}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:47907"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "3-oxo-5-alpha-steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.993262529373169, "span": {"begin": 1860, "end": 1881}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6716"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "3-oxo-5-alpha-steroid 4-dehydrogenase 2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9710528254508972, "span": {"begin": 1860, "end": 1899}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6716"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SRD5A2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9949136972427368, "span": {"begin": 1901, "end": 1907}}], "text": "Gonadotropins are hormones in mammals that cue development of reproductive organs to maturity (Casarini and Simoni 2021; Howard 2021) and the different phases of the estrus cycle (Uenoyama et al. 2021). &nbsp;Gonadotropins are composed of two subunits: a 90-100 amino acid alpha subunit that is identical for all gonadotropins for a species, and a 105-150 amino acid beta subunit that are unique to each gonadotropin but exhibit large similarities in order to interact with alpha subunits (Cahoreau et al 2015). &nbsp;Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and Luteinizing hormone (LH) are gonadotropins of particular interest because of roles in the hypothalamus- pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis, and are released from the anterior pituitary gland (Howard 2021), resulting in increased production of estradiol in the ovaries. &nbsp;   Production of estradiol (E2) by the ovaries has been well-established by the two-cell, two gonadotropin model of steroid biosynthesis (for review see Drummond 2006; Kimura et al. 2007; Palermo 2007; Beevors et al. 2024). Luteinizing hormone stimulates steroid production in theca cells, with follicle-stimulating hormone stimulates steroid production in granulosa cells.    Table 1: List of steroid synthesis enzymes with identifier of enzyme (Uniprot, 2025).               Enzyme            Identifier                  Steroidogenic acute regulatory protein, mitochondrial (STAR)         &nbsp;              Cholesterol side-chain cleavage enzyme, mitochondrial (CYP11A)             EC:1.14.15.6                  3 beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (3B-HSD)            EC:1.1.1.145                  Steroid 17-alpha-hydroxylase (CYP17A1)            EC:1.14.14.19                  17-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (17B-HSD)            EC:1.1.1.105                  Aromatase (CYP19A1)            EC:1.14.14.14                  3-oxo-5-alpha-steroid 4-dehydrogenase 2 (SRD5A2)            EC:1.3.1.22", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:21:15 +0000 2026"}